As part of efforts to enhance productivity, the Accra, Ghana-based Kofi Annan International Peace and Training Centre (KAIPTC) has vowed to provide capacity development to staff of National Oil Spill Detection and Response Agency (NOSDRA) on three thematic areas such as peace support operations, conflict management and security studies. While receiving a 5-man team from KAIPTC in his office, the director general/chief executive officer of NOSDRA, Mr Idris Musa appreciated the centre over the new collaborative arrangement that culminated with one of the staff of the agency undergoing training programme on maritime security and trans-national crimes last year. He stated that NOSDRA was involved in a number of working relationships with other critical stakeholders, including the National Central Bureau of Interpol on crude oil theft. The DG listed the challenges faced by the agency as capacity building, working tools and public sensitisation. Responding, the leader of the team, Colonel Albert Ulrich appreciated NOSDRA’s invaluable contribution towards the exchange of vital information on maritime security, especially crude oil theft and illegal refining, where the agency has been collaborating with Nigerian Navy, military Joint Task Force (JTF), NIMASA, Marine Police and Interpol to end illegal bunkering on the pipelines. 